  <!-- ── Spectral Analysis ── -->
  <h2 id="spectral-analysis">Spectral Analysis &mdash; Understanding Oil Contamination</h2>

  <p>
    Spectral analysis (also known as spectrometric oil analysis) is the standard method for evaluating hydraulic oil condition in extrusion operations. The technique uses light absorption or emission to identify and quantify <strong>dissolved and suspended metals, additives, and contaminant elements</strong> present in an oil sample.
  </p>

  <p>
    A spectral analysis report presents contaminant concentrations as a chart of elements measured in parts per million (ppm). Key elements monitored in extrusion press hydraulic oil include:
  </p>

  <ul>
    <li><strong>Iron (Fe):</strong> Wear indicator from pumps, cylinders, and valve spools. Rising iron levels signal accelerated component wear.</li>
    <li><strong>Copper (Cu):</strong> Wear indicator from bronze bushings, cooler tubes, and hydraulic hose fittings</li>
    <li><strong>Silicon (Si):</strong> External contamination &mdash; dirt and dust ingress through breathers or seals</li>
    <li><strong>Aluminum (Al):</strong> In extrusion presses, this can indicate billet contamination entering the hydraulic circuit or wear from aluminum alloy components</li>
    <li><strong>Sodium (Na) &amp; Potassium (K):</strong> Water contamination indicators &mdash; often from cooler leaks introducing coolant into the hydraulic system</li>
    <li><strong>Zinc (Zn) &amp; Phosphorus (P):</strong> Additive depletion indicators &mdash; declining levels signal the oil's anti-wear package is being consumed</li>
  </ul>

  <p>
    Trending spectral analysis results over time reveals contamination patterns and provides early warning of developing component failures. A centrifuge keeps contaminant levels consistently low, extending the interval before critical thresholds are reached.
  </p>

  <!-- ── Carbon, Degradation & Coke ── -->
  <h2 id="carbon-degradation">Carbon, Degradation, and Coke in Hydraulic Oil</h2>

  <p>
    Extrusion presses subject hydraulic oil to extreme conditions &mdash; pressures exceeding 3,000 PSI and localized temperatures above 250&deg;F at valve orifices and pump clearances. Under these conditions, <strong>oil molecules split apart</strong> through a process called thermal cracking. The result is the formation of carbon-based degradation byproducts:
  </p>

  <ul>
    <li><strong>Carbon Particles:</strong> When hydrocarbon oil molecules fracture under heat and pressure, they leave behind insoluble carbon particles. These sub-micron particles are too small for conventional filters but accumulate rapidly, darkening the oil and forming abrasive suspensions.</li>
    <li><strong>Degradation Acids:</strong> Thermal and oxidative degradation produces organic acids that attack metal surfaces, accelerate seal deterioration, and lower the oil's pH. Acid byproducts also catalyze further oil breakdown, creating a self-accelerating cycle.</li>
    <li><strong>Coke:</strong> Prolonged exposure to extreme heat causes carbon particles to polymerize into hard, varnish-like deposits called coke. Coke adheres to valve spools, servo pistons, and internal passages, restricting flow and causing components to seize.</li>
  </ul>

  <p>
    These three degradation products &mdash; carbon, acids, and coke &mdash; are interconnected. Carbon particles serve as nucleation sites for acid formation. Acids accelerate further cracking. And the accumulating carbon eventually bakes into coke deposits on hot surfaces. The only effective defense is <strong>continuous removal of carbon and degradation byproducts</strong> before they can progress through this cycle.
  </p>

  <!-- ── Domino Effects ── -->
  <h2 id="domino-effects">Domino Effects of Carbon Contamination</h2>

  <p>
    Unchecked carbon contamination in extrusion press hydraulic oil triggers a chain of escalating problems:
  </p>

  <h3>1. Acid Deterioration</h3>
  <p>
    Carbon particles provide a massive surface area for oxidation reactions. As oil oxidizes, it produces organic acids that attack copper alloy components (cooler tubes, bushings), degrade elastomer seals, and corrode ferrous surfaces. Rising acid levels (measured by Total Acid Number, or TAN) indicate the oil is beyond safe operating condition. The acids further destabilize the remaining additive package, stripping anti-wear and anti-foam properties from the fluid.
  </p>

  <h3>2. Grease Contamination</h3>
  <p>
    Carbon particles combine with moisture and degradation acids to form a grease-like sludge that accumulates in low-flow areas of the hydraulic circuit &mdash; reservoir corners, manifold passages, and valve cavities. This sludge restricts flow, insulates heat exchangers (reducing cooling capacity), and provides a breeding ground for further chemical breakdown of the oil.
  </p>

  <h3>3. Coke Formation</h3>
  <p>
    The final stage of carbon contamination is coke &mdash; hard, carbonized deposits that form on hot metal surfaces. In extrusion press hydraulic systems, coke deposits are most destructive on servo valve spools, proportional valve orifices, and pump piston surfaces. Once formed, coke cannot be removed by filtration or flushing; the affected component must be disassembled and cleaned or replaced.
  </p>

  <!-- ── Harmful Effects ── -->
  <h2 id="harmful-effects">Harmful Effects: Seized and Jammed Valves</h2>

  <p>
    The most expensive consequence of hydraulic oil contamination in extrusion is <strong>valve failure</strong>. Carbon, coke, and sludge buildup causes critical hydraulic valves to seize or jam, resulting in immediate press shutdown and extended downtime:
  </p>

  <ul>
    <li>
      <strong>Cartridge Valves:</strong> These high-flow directional valves control the main ram and crosshead movements. Carbon contamination causes the poppet to stick in the open or closed position, resulting in uncontrolled ram movement or complete loss of press function. Cartridge valve replacement requires draining the manifold, removing heavy blocks, and precision reassembly &mdash; typically <strong>1&ndash;2 weeks</strong> of downtime.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Flow Dividers:</strong> Flow divider valves ensure synchronized cylinder movement in multi-ram presses. Contamination causes uneven spool movement, resulting in misaligned rams, uneven extrusion pressure, and poor product quality. Rebuilding a flow divider is precision work requiring <strong>2&ndash;3 weeks</strong> including part procurement.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Servo Valves:</strong> The most contamination-sensitive components in the hydraulic circuit, servo valves control precise ram speed and position. Their internal clearances are measured in microns. Even small amounts of carbon or coke cause erratic control response, position drift, and eventual seizure. Servo valve failure can bring an extrusion press down for <strong>4&ndash;6 weeks</strong> depending on parts availability.
    </li>
  </ul>

  <p>
    A single servo valve failure on a major extrusion press can cost <strong>$50,000&ndash;$150,000</strong> in combined repair costs and lost production. Preventative oil purification eliminates the root cause of these failures.
  </p>

